Path2D

Path2D and PathFollow2D constrain the movement of child nodes

Path2D lets you design a smooth curve with Bezier interpolation, as seen in vector drawing programs like Affinity Designer or Inkscape. The PathFollow2D node moves along a parent Path2D and makes its children follow the path.

You can either draw the path in the viewport or generate curves at runtime. In turn, the two nodes are great for path-following mechanics.

For example, using Path2D and PathFollow2D, you could use the AStar pathfinding algorithm to construct paths for units to follow at runtime in a top-down grid-based game.

Path2D node can work on its own without the PathFollow2D child. We’ll cover this when generating a laser beam that shoots from off-screen onto a target.

On the other hand, PathFollow2D only works as a child of Path2D, where it gets constrained on the parent’s curve.

In this guide, you’ll learn to:

  • Set up the Path2D and PathFollow2D combo for making nodes follow a designated path.
  • Make a player unit move along a path generated using an AStar algorithm in real-time. We’ll also see how to deal with hitpoints that follow the unit without rotating along the path.
  • Generate a random path for a card game for an effective animation.
  • Move a platform on a predefined path in a side-scroll demo.
  • Create a sweeping laser animation with off-screen origin.
  • Use the Path2D and PathFollow2D in a non-standard way to create a directed force field that influences RigidBody2D nodes.

Setting up a Path2D and PathFollow2D to move along the path

To follow a Path2D node’s curve, you must add a PathFollow2D node as a child of it, like so:

To draw a path, you need to add a new Curve2D to the Path2D’s Curve property.

You can then draw the path in the 2D viewport using the toolbar that appears at the top:

Then you can manipulate the location of PathFollow2D along the curve using either its Offset or Unit Offset in the Inspector:

Updating either property automatically updates the other.

Path2D’s key features

The purpose of the Path2D node is to hold the Curve2D resource. This is its key property.

The Curve2D resource

You can either draw the curve in the 2D viewport in the editor or manipulate it in code. Both ways are helpful depending on the case.

To save on performance, the node precalculates points along the curve using the Bake Interval property. This value represents the distance in pixels between two of those points.

By default, the Curve2D resource uses a Bake Interval of 5 pixels, meaning it’ll precalculate one point every 5 pixels.

As we’ll see, this property, combined with PathFollow2D’s Cubic Interp property, can generate smooth paths, even if we have a Curve2D with sharp corners.

Here’s a preview with Bake Interval set to 250 and Cubic Interp both on and off:

Note: If the Bake Interval is too large, the arcs followed by PathFollow2D can end up very different from the smooth curve you drew. For performance reasons, the engine calculates a limited number of vertices when drawing the curve based on the Bake Interval property.

PathFollow2D’s key features

PathFollow2D only works as a child of a Path2D node. Its key features are that it moves and rotates along its parent path.

Offset-based position and rotation

You control the node’s position along the parent path using either the Offset or the Unit Offset property.

Changing either property causes the other to update as well. The main difference is that the Offset is in pixels while the Unit Offset is in the [0, 1] range.

Smooth paths with cubic interpolation

As we saw, the actual path taken by PathFollow2D is influenced by Curve2D’s Bake Interval property.

Especially when Cubic Interp is on, this smooths the interpolation between the cached curve points, even if the curve is created with sharp corners.

Optional rotation along the curve

The other notable feature of PathFollow2D is the Rotate property. If it’s on, the node will also align its rotation to match the curve direction.

The Lookahead property also influences the rotation. Smaller values lead to faster rotations.

Horizontal and vertical offsets

As the name implies, H Offset and V Offset add horizontal and vertical offsets to the position of the PathFollow2D node.

For example, by duplicating the PathFollow2D twice:

And setting the H Offset and V Offset to -150 on one and H Offset to -150 and V Offset to 150 on the other, we get a uniform mob movement:

Although this setup looks very mechanical, if you add a bit of randomness to the H Offset and V Offset properties, it can give interesting results.

Looping and cyclic curves

Finally, when on, the Loop property will force any Offset value outside the Curve2D length to wrap around. This is useful for cyclic paths. We create a cyclic path by having the first and last points coincide.

There’s no need to place the last point of the curve manually. We can generate a final point that coincides perfectly with the first using the Close Curve button from the toolbar:

How to use Path2D and PathFollow2D in practice

In this section, we’ll look at standard examples of using the Path2D and PathFollow2D combo and some more creative cases.

Real-time paths for the AStar algorithm

In this example, we have a top-down game that uses a TileMap and the AStar algorithm to construct a path for the player ship to follow.

We use the Path2D and PathFollow2D combo to create real-time paths on player mouse click. The path starts at the current ship position and ends at the center of the clicked tile.

We’ll also look at handling an attached UI element that follows the player ship but doesn’t rotate with it.

To find and follow paths, we use the following nodes:

  • A TileMap serves as the game’s grid. We treat occupied cells as obstacles.
  • A Path2D with a child PathFollow2D to respectively generate a curve and follow it.
    • We add a character as a child of the PathFollow2D, a Sprite, that’ll automatically move along with its parent.

We make sure to turn off the PathFollow2D’s Loop property. Otherwise, the ship will restart the path movement from the beginning forever.

We then reference our necessary nodes from code:

# We reference our scene's three key nodes and use them for pathfinding.
onready var _tilemap: TileMap = $TileMap
onready var _path: Path2D = $Path2D
onready var _path_follow: PathFollow2D = $Path2D/PathFollow2D

Moving the PathFollow2D node along the Path2D’s Curve is done in _process(). By default, we disable _process() and only enable it when a new curve is calculated based on the player mouse input.

We need a few variables for calculating the player ship speed:

## The ship's maximum speed in pixels per second.
const SPEED_MAX := 550.0

var _acceleration := 1000.0
## The ship's current speed in pixels per second.
var _speed := 0.0

And then, in the _process() function:

# We reference our scene's three key nodes and use them for pathfinding.
onready var _tilemap: TileMap = $TileMap
onready var _path: Path2D = $Path2D
onready var _path_follow: PathFollow2D = $Path2D/PathFollow2D

func _process(delta: float) -> void:
    _speed = min(_speed + _acceleration * delta, SPEED_MAX)
    _path_follow.offset += _speed * delta

    if _path_follow.offset >= _path.curve.get_baked_length():
        _speed = 0.0
        set_process(false)

To construct the curve based on the AStar algorithm and issue the move command, we:

  1. Get the AStar path.
  2. Clear the current Path2D Curve and add the points from step one to it.
  3. Enable _process() to start the ship movement.

To get the ship to move along the path, we call two functions, find_path_to() and move_along().

func _unhandled_input(event: InputEvent) -> void:
    if event.is_action_pressed("click"):
        move_along(find_path_to(event.position))

The find_path_to() function asks the AStar2D object for a path, an array of grid coordinates to move to the target position.

## Gets the `AStar` point-path given by the `PathFollow2D` current position and the
## input `mouse_position`.
func find_path_to(mouse_position: Vector2) -> PoolVector2Array:
    var out: PoolVector2Array = []

    # First get the start and finish `AStar` indices based on `PathFollow2D` and respectively
    # the mouse click locations.
    var start_index := xy_to_index(_tilemap.world_to_map(_path_follow.position))
    var finish_index := xy_to_index(_tilemap.world_to_map(mouse_position))
    if _astar.has_point(start_index) and _astar.has_point(finish_index):
        out = _astar.get_point_path(start_index, finish_index)

    return out

We define two utility functions to convert 2D coordinates to unique indices and vice-versa. We need this as the pathfinding algorithm works with indices.

# We use the following two functions to convert values between grid coordinates
# and indices.
func xy_to_index(offset: Vector2) -> int:
    return int(offset.x + _tilemap_rect.size.x * offset.y)


func index_to_xy(index: int) -> Vector2:
    return Vector2(index % int(_tilemap_rect.size.x), index / int(_tilemap_rect.size.x))

Last is the move_along() function which takes the path output by find_path_to() and updates the Path2D node’s curve for the ship to move to the target.

## Updates the `Path2D.curve` property based on the input `AStar` point-path and starts the
## player movement.
func move_along(path: Array) -> void:
    if path.empty():
        return

    # Clear the curve points and add the current `PathFollow2D` position as the first point.
    # This way, we can calculate new paths mid-movement.
    _path.curve.clear_points()
    _path.curve.add_point(_path_follow.position)

    # We skip the first points since we already added the `PathFollow2D` position.
    for index in range(1, path.size()):
        # Get point in world coordinates and correct for tile center.
        var point := _tilemap.map_to_world(path[index])
        point += _tilemap.cell_size / 2
        _path.curve.add_point(point)

    # Reset the `PathFollow2D` offset and enable `_process()` to start the movement.
    _path_follow.offset = 0.0
    set_process(true)

Player-following health bar

We often need to make UI widgets follow moving entities, like a life bar that displays right above a ship.

However, if you add the bar as a child of the ship, it will rotate with its parent.

When the entity moves along a path using PathFollow2D, there are several ways we can go about moving the UI at an offset:

  1. Create an extra PathFollow2D specially made for the health bar and turn off Rotate in the Inspector. In this case, we need to sync its offset property with the other PathFollow2D node in code.
  2. Use a RemoteTransform2D node to forward the ship’s position to the life bar with an offset.

We explore the second option here because it doesn’t require any extra code.

We start with the same setup as the previous example: a TileMap for the level, a Path2D, and a PathFollow2D.

As a child of the PathFollow2D, we have a RemoteTransform2D node to forward the player’s position to the health bar.

We separate the health bar from the PathFollow2D to keep it upright. As the ProgressBar node we use is a UI node, the RemoteTransform2D couldn’t directly control it.

This is why it has a parent Node2D named Health.

It’s up to you to give the health an appropriate offset relative to the parent Node2D:

As for the RemoteTransform2D node, we assign the ProgressBar node’s parent to Remote Path and turn off Rotation:

Now, whenever we update the PathFollow2D’s Offset property, the RemoteTransform2D also updates the placement of the health bar without affecting its rotation:

You can learn more about using the RemoteTransform2D node in the RemoteTransform2D guide.

Random paths for card games

In this demo, we animate cards moving from the player’s hand to the table slots.

To do so, we generate random motion paths.

This example uses this scene setup:

  • The Slots are locations to which the cards can move.
  • Each card lives in the Hand and is composed of:
    • A Path2D with a child PathFollow2D.
    • As a child of the PathFollow2D, we have the card’s visuals.
    • We use a Tween node to animate the PathFollow2D’s offset and move the card along the path.

To learn more about designing a card, check out the PanelContainer guide.

To animate the cards, we calculate a path with three points, where the first and last are:

  1. The first point is the card’s position.
  2. The last point is the position of the first empty slot from the left.

To add variety to the animation, we construct the curve’s middle point by first calculating the average position between the first and last point.

Then we add a random perturbation horizontally.

Given an array of target positions, a RandomNumberGenerator, and references to the relevant nodes, we can construct a curve when the player clicks on a card.

We attach the following code to each card.

## Stores the position of every slot the card can move to.
## See `setup()` below for its initialization.
var _slot_positions := []
var _rng := RandomNumberGenerator.new()

onready var _path_follow: PathFollow2D = $PathFollow2D
onready var _card: Node2D = $PathFollow2D/BoardCard
# Each card has a visual border we use to detect when the player hovers and
# clicks the card. You can do that with any Control node.
onready var _card_border: PanelContainer = $PathFollow2D/BoardCard/CardBorder
onready var _tween: Tween = $Tween

func setup(slot_positions: Array) -> void:
    _slot_positions = slot_positions

We handle this interaction in the _on_CardBorder_gui_input() function. We first connect to the UI node’s signals in _ready():

func _ready() -> void:
    _card_border.connect("gui_input", self, "_on_CardBorder_gui_input")
    _card_border.connect("mouse_entered", self, "_on_CardBorder_mouse_entered_exited", [true])
    _card_border.connect("mouse_exited", self, "_on_CardBorder_mouse_entered_exited", [false])
    _rng.randomize()

And for the actual path construction:

# The gui_input signal emits when the player applies input to the node, for
# example, by clicking on it. It won't trigger if the player clicks elsewhere on
# the screen.
func _on_CardBorder_gui_input(event: InputEvent) -> void:
    if event.is_action_pressed("click"):
        # Bring the card on top of the others using the `_slot_positions` size.
        z_index = _slot_positions.size()

        # Get the next slot position, this will also shrink the array.
        var slot_position: Vector2 = _slot_positions.pop_back()

        # Find the mean vertical position between the card and the slot and apply
        # a random horizontal offset for added variation.
        var offset: Vector2 = (_path_follow.position + slot_position) / 2.0
        offset.x += _rng.randf_range(-200, 200)

        # Add the points to the curve: the current card position, the middle offset and
        # the final slot position.
        curve.clear_points()
        curve.add_point(_path_follow.position)
        curve.add_point(offset)
        curve.add_point(slot_position)

        # Here, we animate the card moving along the path.
        _tween.stop_all()
        _tween.interpolate_property(
            _path_follow, "unit_offset", 0, 1, 0.6, Tween.TRANS_QUAD, Tween.EASE_OUT
        )
        # We animate the card going up when hovering it with the mouse. So we
        # need to move it back to its original position quickly to avoid having
        # it offset from the card slot.
        _tween.interpolate_property(
            _card, "position:y", _card.position.y, 0, 0.1, Tween.TRANS_CUBIC, Tween.EASE_IN, 0.7
        )
        _tween.interpolate_callback(self, 0.8, "set_z_index", 0)
        _tween.start()

        # Once the player placed a card, they shouldn't be able to click it
        # anymore. That's why we disconnect from the signals.
        _card_border.disconnect("mouse_entered", self, "_on_CardBorder_mouse_entered_exited")
        _card_border.disconnect("mouse_exited", self, "_on_CardBorder_mouse_entered_exited")
        _card_border.disconnect("gui_input", self, "_on_CardBorder_gui_input")

Side-scroller platforms following a complex path

In this example, we construct a platform following an arbitrary curve instead of the regular horizontal or vertical motions.

Interestingly enough, this demo doesn’t need any code other than the code for player movement and perhaps interactables, like the coin.

To make the Platform do a complete cycle, we animate the PathFollow2D’s unit_offset property from 0 to 1:

I picked an 8 second long animation for the cycle, made sure to autoplay the Move animation, and made it loop.

Because the Player is a KinematicBody2D node, we need to set the AnimationPlayer -> Process Mode to Physics. Otherwise, you’ll get jitters and bugs when walking on moving platforms.

This is because we move characters using _physics_process() in Godot: we need the animations to synchronize with physics frames for physics interactions to work reliably.

Paths as force fields

Thinking outside the box, we can use the Path2D and PathFollow2D combo for other purposes, apart from constraining nodes’ movement on curves.

In this demo, we use paths to construct a force field that directs the movement of RigidBody2D nodes:

To start us off, we have this scene setup:

The Field contains two paths we use to apply a force to nearby asteroids. The asteroids live under the Asteroids node.

On the Path2D nodes, we defined a few export variables for easy access in the Inspector:

The idea is that the force will be strongest if an asteroid is right on the path, with a value of Force Size.

It then decays up to Decay Distance following the Decay Curve profile.

export var force_size := 500.0
export var decay_curve: Curve = Curve.new()
export var decay_distance := 500.0

On the root node, we have a script for calculating the force based on the paths and applying it to the RigidBody2D nodes under Asteroids.

Start by getting references to the appropriate nodes:

onready var _field: Node2D = $Field
onready var _asteroids: Node2D = $Asteroids

We can calculate the force at a given point any way we want, based on the path. This is how we do it here:

## Calculate a force at the given input position, based on the proximity to the
## available paths.
func get_force(input_position: Vector2) -> Vector2:
    var force := Vector2.ZERO

    for path in _field.get_children():
        var path_follow: PathFollow2D = path.get_node("PathFollow2D")

        # Move `PathFollow2D` to the closest point to `input_position`, on the curve.
        path_follow.offset = path.curve.get_closest_offset(input_position)

        # Calculate the force at `distance` given the decay `Curve`.
        var vector_from_input_position := path_follow.position - input_position
        var force_size_at_distance = path.force_size * path.decay_curve.interpolate_baked(
            min(vector_from_input_position.length() / path.decay_distance, 1.0)
        )
        force += force_size_at_distance * path_follow.transform.x

    return force

We calculate the total force by adding the contribution to all paths under the Field node.

Then for every RigidBody2D, in our case called PushedAsteroid, we apply the force:

func _physics_process(_delta: float) -> void:
    for asteroid in _asteroids.get_children():
        asteroid.applied_force = get_force(asteroid.position)

Laser swiping effect

We’ll see how to fire a laser from off-screen onto a moving target for our last demonstrating.

The setup for this scene is as follows:

The Ship moves in an infinite loop, based on the Path2DShip curve.

The laser firing mechanism works like this:

  1. Pick a random position on Path2DLaser.
  2. Rotate the Line2D Target node randomly for variation.
  3. Swipe the Line2D Laser over the segment defined by Target using the Tween node.

We fire the laser every time Timer emits the timeout signal.

We’re using the RemoteTransform2D node under PathFollow2D to make Target follow the Ship node.

I gave it a Position offset so that the laser swiping starts at the tip of the Ship because it’s a moving object.

For Laser, I used a Width of 4, its Color is #eb564b, and I turned Antialiased on for a smoother look.

For Target, I used a Width of 1, the same Color, #eb564b and manually defined Points for a symmetrical horizontal segment.

We also make sure to turn off Rotation because we want to align Target randomly for each shot.

To start coding, we store the desired laser swipe duration in a constant and a RandomNumberGenerator to randomize the laser.

We also store references to all the nodes we need in the script.

## The duration of the laser beam's swipe animation in seconds.
const LASER_ANIMATION_DURATION := 0.4

# We use a random number generator to randomize the angle of the swipe
# animation, as well as the position of the laser outside the screen.
var _rng := RandomNumberGenerator.new()

onready var _path_follow: PathFollow2D = $Path2DShip/PathFollow2D
onready var _path_laser_curve: Curve2D = $Path2DLaser.curve
onready var _laser: Line2D = $Laser
onready var _target: Line2D = $Target
onready var _tween: Tween = $Tween
onready var _timer: Timer = $Timer

As I said, we fire the laser every time the Timer emits the timeout signal.

We also need to reset the Laser points at the end of each swipe. So we prepare the connections and defaults in the _ready() function:

func _ready() -> void:
    _rng.randomize()
    _timer.connect("timeout", self, "_on_Timer_timeout")
    _tween.connect("tween_all_completed", _laser, "set_visible", [false])
    _laser.points = PoolVector2Array([Vector2.ZERO, Vector2.ZERO])
    _laser.visible = false

We finish off with the _on_Timer_timout() and the _animate_laser_swipe() functions:

func _on_Timer_timeout() -> void:
    # Rotate `Target` randomly for some variation.
    _target.rotation = _rng.randf_range(0, PI / 2)

    # Get a random location off-sreen, on `Path2DLaser`. This is the origin point for
    # the incoming laser.
    _laser.points[0] = _path_laser_curve.interpolate_baked(
        _rng.randf_range(0, _path_laser_curve.get_baked_length())
    )

    # Since the target is controlled by a `RemoteTransform2D` and a `PathFollow2D`, we need to
    # convert its points in global coordinates.
    var target: PoolVector2Array = _target.transform.xform(_target.points)

    _tween.stop_all()
    _tween.interpolate_method(
        self, "_animate_laser_swipe", target[0], target[1], LASER_ANIMATION_DURATION,
        Tween.TRANS_LINEAR, Tween.EASE_IN
    )
    _tween.start()
    # Seeking forces the tween to update the animation state. Otherwise, the laser's position won't
    # update until the next frame, causing visual artifacts.
    _tween.seek(0.0)
    _laser.visible = true

    # We wait for a random amount of time between one and two seconds before
    # firing again.
    _timer.wait_time = _rng.randf_range(1, 2)
    _plop.restart()


## Gets called on every `Tween` step. Since the origin of the laser is fixed, we swipe by
## changing the second point on the Line2D node.
func _animate_laser_swipe(point: Vector2) -> void:
    _laser.points[1] = point
    _plop.position = point

Your questions

How do we create regular geometric paths (ellipses, rectangles, etc.)?

There are no built-in methods to create regular 2D shapes in Godot. You’ll have to write a geometric library to use as either a plug-in or in real-time.

One way to do it is to rely on the internal Godot code for some built-in shapes for the CollisionShape2D node.

The code is simple enough that it can be converted to GDScript without much hassle.

For example, we can find the CapsuleShape2D._get_points() backend implementation, and either copy it and convert it to a GDScript function or use it as a starting point for making your implementation.

You can use this method to convert any other Shape2D resources internal function for your purpose.
